"Bobe Quinteros R., Behrensmeyer A.K., Carrasco Ormazábal G.","Paleoclimate and faunal evolution in the Plio-Pleistocene of Africa and South America [Paleoclima y evolución faunísta en el Plio-Pleistoceno de África y América del Sur]",2004,"Ameghiniana","41","4",,"641","649",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-14844356766&partnerID=40&md5=35a6fdd8979382b147bcb6a5d241fd1c","Department of Anthropology, State Univ. of New York at Buffalo, Buffalo, NY 14261-0026, United States; Smithsonian Inst. Evol. Terrestrial, NHB MRC 121, PO Box 37012, Washington, DC 20013-7012, United States; Ctro. de Divulgacion Biogeografica, San Bernardo, Chile","Bobe Quinteros, R., Department of Anthropology, State Univ. of New York at Buffalo, Buffalo, NY 14261-0026, United States, Smithsonian Inst. Evol. Terrestrial, NHB MRC 121, PO Box 37012, Washington, DC 20013-7012, United States; Behrensmeyer, A.K., Smithsonian Inst. Evol. Terrestrial, NHB MRC 121, PO Box 37012, Washington, DC 20013-7012, United States; Carrasco Ormazábal, G., Ctro. de Divulgacion Biogeografica, San Bernardo, Chile","Climatic change is often hypothesized to be a major variable in forcing evolutionary change. Recent work on Pliocene and Pleistocene fossil mammals from the Turkana Basin of Kenya and Ethiopia shows that climate may play an important role in the spread of savanna environments, and thus in the increasing abundance of mammals adapted to open and seasonally and conditions. If global climate change is behind some of these trends in East Africa, we hypothesize that similar patterns of faunal change may occur elsewhere. An analysis of fossil mammals from the Pampean region of Argentina shows an increase in the number of species adapted to open and seasonally and conditions through the Plio-Pleistocene. The South American pattern is not identical to the East African pattern, but both show a significant increase in open and arid adapted mammals shortly after 2 million years ago, at the very beginning of the Pleistocene. Although global climate change may be invoked as a common cause of these intercontinental trends, local and regional geography and tectonics play a critical role in modulating the global signal. © Asociación Paleontológica Argentina.","Africa; Argentina; Mammals; Paleoclimate; Pleistocene; Pliocene","climate change; evolution; fossil assemblage; mammal; Pleistocene; Pliocene",,,,,,"Agustí, J., Rook, L., Andrews, P., (1999) Evolution of Neogene Terrestrial Ecosystems in Europe, p. 512. , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Alberdi, M.T., Prado, J.L., Los équidos de América del Sur (1995) Evolución Biológica Y Climática De La Región Pampeana Durante Los Últimos Cinco Millones De Años, pp. 295-308. , M.T. Alberdi, G. Leone y E.P. Tonni (eds.), Monografías 12. Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, Madrid; Alberdi, M.T., Prado, J.L., Los mastodontes de América del Sur (1995) Evolución Biológica Y Climática De La Región Pampeana Durante Los Últimos Cinco Millones De Años, pp. 279-292. , M.T. Alberdi, G. Leone y E.P. Tonni (eds.), Monografías 12. Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, Madrid; Alberdi, M.T., Leone, G., Tonni, E.P., Evolución Biológica y Climática de la Región Pampeana Durante los últimos Cinco Millones de Años (1995), p. 423. , Monografías 12, Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, MadridAlemseged, Z., L'hominidé Omo-323: Sa position phylétique et son environnement dans le cadre de l'évolution des communautés de mammiféres du Plio-Pléistocène dans la basse vallée de l'Omo (Ethiopie) (1998), [Ph.D., Muséum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris. Inédita]Benzécri, J.P., (1992) Correspondence Analysis Handbook, p. 688. , Dekker, New York; Bernor, R.L., Fahlbusch, V., Mittmann, H.W., (1996) The Evolution of Western Neogene Mammal Faunas, p. 487. , Columbia University Press, New York; Boaz, N.T., Paleoecology of Plio-Pleistocene Hominidae in the lower Omo basin, Ethiopia (1977), p. 234. , [Ph.D., University of California, Berkeley, Inédit